Let's think step by step. Let's consider all possible pairs of the first six prime numbers: \begin{align*}
(2,3)&,(2,5),(2,7),(2,11),(2,13);\\
(3,5)&,(3,7),(3,11),(3,13);\\
(5,7)&,(5,11),(5,13);\\
(7,11)&,(7,13);\\
(11,13)
\end{align*}This makes a total of $15$ possibilities. Out of these, the following pairs consist of two even or two odd numbers: \begin{align*}
(2,2)&;(2,not\,2)\\
(not\,2,not\,2)&;(not\,2,2)\qquad\text{Here (2,not\,2)=is the same as (not\,2,2)}
\end{align*}There are no ways to get two even numbers since there is only one even prime. There are nine ways to get two odd numbers, namely those not including 2. Thus, there are a total of 9 possibilities out of 15 total,
